1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,887
Saint Pacian's Three Letters to Sympronian the Novatian.

2
00:00:03,887 --> 00:00:07,008
Letter One On the Catholic Name

3
00:00:07,008 --> 00:00:09,310
Pacianus to his brother Sympronian, greetings.

4
00:00:09,310 --> 00:00:19,823
If it is not a carnal intention but, as I believe, a spiritual calling that prompts you to examine the faith of Catholic truth from us, then you should have indicated which different beliefs you were following.

5
00:00:19,823 --> 00:00:25,981
You seem to have started far from the source and origin of the principal Church, not holding to its fountain and beginning.

6
00:00:25,981 --> 00:00:30,487
You should have revealed what specifically caused you to break from the unity of our body.

7
00:00:30,487 --> 00:00:33,290
For those parts that require healing need to be exposed.

8
00:00:33,290 --> 00:00:37,195
Now, with the matter hidden, we do not see which parts of us most need curing.

9
00:00:37,195 --> 00:00:41,951
So many heresies have arisen from the Christian head that the volume of their names is immense.

10
00:00:41,951 --> 00:00:55,568
For instance, to omit the heretics among the Jews, like Dositheus the Samaritan, the Sadducees, and the Pharisees: it would be too long to count how many emerged during the times of the apostles: Simon Magus, Menander, Nicolaus, and others whom obscure fame has concealed.

11
00:00:55,568 --> 00:01:04,229
What about later times with Ebion, Apelles, Marcion, Valentinus, and Cerdon: and not long after them, the Cataphrygians and Novatians, not to mention the more recent swarms?

12
00:01:04,229 --> 00:01:06,231
So who should I first refute in writing?

13
00:01:06,231 --> 00:01:09,485
The paper will not hold all their names if you wish to list them.

14
00:01:09,485 --> 00:01:15,243
Except that in your writings, which condemn repentance everywhere, you declare yourself aligned with the Phrygians.

15
00:01:15,243 --> 00:01:25,055
But even among these, their error is so manifold and diverse that it is not just one thing in them that opposes repentance, but rather, like the many-headed Hydra, several aspects must be cut off.

16
00:01:25,655 --> 00:01:36,409
If your intention is not carnal but a spiritual calling, Lord, and you seek to examine our faith in the Catholic truth, you should have clearly indicated which teachings you intend to follow and how they differ.

17
00:01:36,409 --> 00:01:44,105
You, who began far from the source and did not adhere to the origins of the main Church, should have revealed the primary cause that divided our unity.

18
00:01:44,105 --> 00:01:46,653
For those parts that need healing must be exposed.

19
00:01:46,653 --> 00:01:51,597
Now, with the letters, so to speak, closed, we do not see which parts need our special attention.

20
00:01:51,597 --> 00:01:56,439
So many heresies have emerged from the Christian faith that the list of their names is immense.

21
00:01:56,439 --> 00:02:01,382
To set aside the heretics of the Jews: Dositheus the Samaritan, the Sadducees, and the Pharisees.

22
00:02:01,382 --> 00:02:08,772
It would take too long to count how many arose during the apostles' times: Simon Magus, Menander, Nicolaus, and others whom history has obscured.

23
00:02:08,772 --> 00:02:12,646
What about later times with Ebion, Apelles, Marcion, Valentinus, and Cerdon?

24
00:02:12,646 --> 00:02:16,825
And soon after them, the Cataphrygians and Novatians, not to mention newer groups?

25
00:02:16,825 --> 00:02:18,914
Who then should I refute first by letter?

26
00:02:18,914 --> 00:02:21,972
The names of all would not fit on a single page if you wish.

27
00:02:21,972 --> 00:02:27,324
Except that in your writings, condemning repentance everywhere, you declare agreement with the Phrygians.

28
00:02:27,324 --> 00:02:36,803
But in those very writings, dear Lord, the error is so varied and diverse that it is not just one thing against repentance, but many issues like the Hydra's heads that must be addressed.

29
00:02:36,803 --> 00:02:38,485
First, they rely on many authors.

30
00:02:38,485 --> 00:02:44,040
For I think even the Greek Blastus is among them: Theodotus and Praxeas also taught your people at some time.

31
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:49,850
Those notable Phrygians, who falsely claim to be inspired by Leucius, boast that they were instructed by Proculus.

32
00:02:49,850 --> 00:02:57,495
Following Montanus, Maximilla, and Priscilla, they stirred up many controversies about the Paschal day, the Paraclete, the apostles, and the prophets.

33
00:02:57,495 --> 00:03:02,133
And many other issues, like this about the Catholic name and the forgiveness of repentance.

34
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,015
Therefore, if we want to discuss all these matters, we need your full attention.

35
00:03:07,015 --> 00:03:12,838
Even if I can't fully instruct you on these topics, we must still serve those seeking knowledge in any way possible.

36
00:03:12,838 --> 00:03:17,909
To inform you, we will briefly talk about the subjects you've deemed important enough to write about.

37
00:03:17,909 --> 00:03:22,728
If you want to understand our beliefs more fully, you need to speak more plainly about your own.

38
00:03:22,728 --> 00:03:27,798
This way, by asking clearly, you won't leave us wondering whether you're questioning or provoking us.

39
00:03:27,798 --> 00:03:31,964
As for the current matters, first of all, I ask you not to give authority to error.

40
00:03:31,964 --> 00:03:36,783
You mentioned that no one in the entire world could refute or persuade you against your beliefs.

41
00:03:36,783 --> 00:03:39,795
Even if we are unskilled, the Spirit of God is most skilled.

42
00:03:39,795 --> 00:03:43,410
And even if we are unfaithful, God is faithful, who cannot deny Himself.

43
00:03:43,410 --> 00:03:45,217
Second Timothy, Chapter 2, Verse 13.

44
00:03:45,217 --> 00:03:49,383
Moreover, for a long time, it was not permitted to contend with the priests of God.

45
00:03:49,383 --> 00:04:44,903
The Apostle says, "We have no such custom, nor does the Church of God." First Corinthians, Chapter 11, Verse 16.
After a single admonition, as you know, a contentious person should be avoided. Titus, Chapter 3, Verse 10.
But who can persuade someone against their will? Therefore, brother, it is your fault, not theirs, if no one has persuaded you of what is best. Even today, you have the power to disregard our writings if you prefer to reject them rather than accept them.
Furthermore, many resisted the Lord Himself and His apostles. The truth cannot persuade anyone unless they agree with it through their own faith. So, my lord, we did not write with the confidence that we could persuade a resistant person, but with the faith that we would not deny the path to good peace to one who is willing.
If this is in your mind and heart, there is no struggle with the name Catholic. If our people attain this through God, there is no need to question, with divine authority preceding. If through man, when usurped, it must be exposed. If the name is good, it does not receive hatred. If bad, it lacks envy.

46
00:04:45,456 --> 00:04:52,434
First, they rely on many authors:
I believe that even the Greek Blastus is among them; Theodotus and Praxeas also once taught your people.

47
00:04:52,434 --> 00:05:04,570
Notable Phrygians, who claim to be inspired by Leucius and instructed by Proculus,:
Following Montanus, Maximilla, and Priscilla, they have stirred up many controversies about the Passover day, the Paraclete, the apostles, and the prophets.

48
00:05:04,570 --> 00:05:08,615
And many other issues, like the Catholic name and the forgiveness of repentance.

49
00:05:08,615 --> 00:05:22,117
Therefore, if we want to examine all these things, a teachable presence is needed:
If I didn't sufficiently instruct you on these matters you wrote about, I will briefly address them for your sake because it is necessary to serve those who wonder in any way possible.

50
00:05:22,117 --> 00:05:31,270
If you wish to know more fully about our side, you must openly confess your own; so that by consulting unclearly, you do not make us unsure whether you are questioning or provoking.

51
00:05:31,270 --> 00:05:41,939
Regarding the present matters, first of all, I ask you not to lend authority to error for the reason you mentioned, that throughout the whole world there is no one who could refute you or persuade you otherwise.

52
00:05:41,939 --> 00:05:49,676
For even if we are unskilled, the Spirit of God is most skilled; and if we are unfaithful, God is faithful, who cannot deny himself Second Timothy, 2:13.

53
00:05:49,676 --> 00:05:53,418
Furthermore, it is not allowed to contend long against the priests of God.

54
00:05:53,418 --> 00:05:58,475
The Apostle says, we do not have such a custom, nor does the Church of God First Corinthians, 11:16.

55
00:05:58,475 --> 00:06:02,571
After one correction Titus, 3:10, as you know, the contentious person is avoided.

56
00:06:02,571 --> 00:06:04,897
But who can persuade someone who is unwilling?

57
00:06:04,897 --> 00:06:09,499
Therefore, brother, it is your fault, not theirs, if no one persuaded you of what was best.

58
00:06:09,499 --> 00:06:15,364
Even today, it is within your power to disregard our writings if you prefer to defeat them rather than approve them.

59
00:06:15,364 --> 00:06:22,646
However, many resisted the Lord himself and his apostles; and the truth could not persuade anyone unless they agreed with it by their own faith.

60
00:06:23,304 --> 00:06:27,703
Therefore, Lord, we haven't written with the confidence to persuade someone who resists.

61
00:06:27,703 --> 00:06:32,053
Instead, we've written with faith that we shouldn't deny access to those seeking peace.

62
00:06:32,053 --> 00:06:36,553
If this aligns with your mind and heart, there will be no struggle over the Catholic name.

63
00:06:36,553 --> 00:06:41,353
For if our people achieve this through God, there's no need to question, given divine authority.

64
00:06:41,353 --> 00:06:44,353
If through man, whenever it’s usurped, it should be exposed.

65
00:06:44,353 --> 00:06:47,753
If the name is good, it won’t receive hatred; if bad, it lacks envy.

66
00:06:47,753 --> 00:06:50,852
I hear that the Novatians are named after Novatus or Novatian.

67
00:06:50,852 --> 00:06:53,552
However, I don’t accuse the name, but the sect itself.

68
00:06:53,552 --> 00:06:57,152
Similarly, no one has accused Montanus or the Phrygians over their name.

69
00:06:57,152 --> 00:07:00,252
You might say, under the apostles, no one was called Catholic.

70
00:07:00,252 --> 00:07:01,752
So be it, let that be allowed.

71
00:07:01,752 --> 00:07:16,502
When heresies arose after the apostles, trying to tear and divide God's dove and queen into parts with various names, didn’t the apostolic people demand a name to distinguish the unity of the uncorrupted people so that the pure virgin of God wouldn’t be torn apart by the errors of some members?

72
00:07:16,502 --> 00:07:19,651
Wasn't it fitting to mark the principal head with its own name?

73
00:07:19,651 --> 00:07:27,051
Suppose I entered a populous city today and found Marcionites, Apollinarians, Cataphrygians, Novatians, and others who called themselves Christians.

74
00:07:27,051 --> 00:07:31,151
How would I recognize the congregation of my people if it weren’t called Catholic?

75
00:07:31,151 --> 00:07:34,001
Come on, who has granted such names to the other peoples?

76
00:07:34,001 --> 00:07:37,101
Why do so many cities and nations have their own descriptions?

77
00:07:37,101 --> 00:07:43,601
The very one who questions the Catholic name wouldn’t know the reason for his own name if I asked where it was handed down to him.

78
00:07:43,601 --> 00:07:47,600
Certainly, it wasn’t borrowed from man, as it has endured for so many centuries.

79
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:53,100
This Catholic name doesn’t sound like Marcion, Apelles, or Montanus, nor does it take heretics as its authors.

80
00:07:53,100 --> 00:08:03,100
The Holy Spirit, whom God sent from heaven as a teacher and comforter to the apostles, has taught many of us; reason, as Paul says, and honesty, and, as he says, nature itself have taught many things.

81
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:03,350
What?

82
00:08:03,350 --> 00:08:10,300
Do we have little authority from the apostolic men, little from the first priests, little from the most blessed martyr and teacher Cyprian?

83
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:12,994
Do we want to teach the teacher?

84
00:08:12,994 --> 00:08:22,659
Are we wiser than him, and are we driven by the spirit of the flesh against him, whom the noble blood and the crown of the most illustrious passion of the eternal God have produced as a witness?

85
00:08:22,659 --> 00:08:28,687
What about all those priests from different regions, whom the same peace united with Cyprian throughout the entire world?

86
00:08:28,687 --> 00:08:32,424
What about all those aged bishops, all those martyrs, all those confessors?

87
00:08:32,424 --> 00:08:32,822
Come on.

88
00:08:32,822 --> 00:08:37,356
If they were not suitable authors by claiming this name, will we be suitable by denying it?

89
00:08:37,356 --> 00:08:42,637
Will our authority be followed by the fathers, and will the antiquity of the saints yield to be corrected?

90
00:08:42,637 --> 00:08:46,673
Will the times, now decaying with vices, erase the canons of apostolic antiquity?

91
00:08:46,673 --> 00:08:55,092
I hear Novatians being called after Novatus or Novatian:
however, I do not accuse the sect by their name;
nor did anyone object to the name of Montanus or the Phrygians.

92
00:08:55,092 --> 00:08:58,331
But you will say, under the apostles, no one was called Catholic.

93
00:08:58,331 --> 00:08:59,576
Let it be so, allow that.

94
00:08:59,576 --> 00:09:15,668
When heresies arose after the apostles and tried to tear and divide the dove of God and the queen into parts under different names:
didn't the apostolic flock ask for its own name to distinguish the unity of the uncorrupted people, so that the virgin of God would not be torn apart by the error of some through the members?

95
00:09:15,668 --> 00:09:19,256
Wasn't it fitting for the principal head to be marked with its own name?

96
00:09:19,256 --> 00:09:31,960
Suppose I entered a populous city today and found Marcionites, Apollinarians, Cataphrygians, Novatians, and others of that kind, who called themselves Christians:
by what name would I recognize the congregation of my people if it were not called Catholic?

97
00:09:31,960 --> 00:09:34,451
Come on, who gave such names to the other peoples?

98
00:09:34,451 --> 00:09:37,291
Why does each city, each nation have its own description?

99
00:09:37,291 --> 00:09:43,767
The one who questions the Catholic name would not know the reason for his own name if I asked from where it was handed down to me.

100
00:09:43,767 --> 00:09:48,251
Certainly, it was not borrowed from a man, that which has not fallen through so many ages.

101
00:09:48,251 --> 00:09:53,682
The name Catholic does not sound like Marcion, nor Apelles, nor Montanus, nor does it take heretical authors.

102
00:09:53,682 --> 00:10:02,849
The Holy Spirit has taught us many things, whom God sent from heaven to the apostles as a comforter and teacher;
much reason, as Paul says, and honesty, and, as he says, nature itself.

103
00:10:02,849 --> 00:10:03,347
What then?

104
00:10:04,344 --> 00:10:10,330
Do we give little authority to the apostolic men, the first priests, or the blessed martyr and teacher Cyprian?

105
00:10:10,330 --> 00:10:12,056
Do we want to teach the teacher?

106
00:10:12,056 --> 00:10:13,351
Are we wiser than he is?

107
00:10:13,351 --> 00:10:20,632
Are we driven by worldly desires against him, whom noble blood and the crown of a great passion have made a witness of the eternal God?

108
00:10:20,632 --> 00:10:26,133
What about all the priests across different places, united in peace with Cyprian throughout the world?

109
00:10:26,133 --> 00:10:29,369
What about the elderly bishops, the martyrs, the confessors?

110
00:10:29,369 --> 00:10:29,800
Come on.

111
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:34,924
If they were not suitable authorities by claiming this name, will we be suitable by denying it?

112
00:10:34,924 --> 00:10:37,459
Will our authority surpass that of the fathers?

113
00:10:37,459 --> 00:10:39,886
Will we correct the traditions of the saints?

114
00:10:39,886 --> 00:10:43,985
Will our current, vice-ridden times erase the canons of apostolic antiquity?

115
00:10:43,985 --> 00:10:48,192
But do not be troubled, brother: Christian is my name, Catholic is my surname.

116
00:10:48,192 --> 00:10:50,511
The former calls me; the latter defines me.

117
00:10:50,511 --> 00:10:53,154
By this, I am approved; by that, I am identified.

118
00:10:53,154 --> 00:11:03,779
If the meaning of the word Catholic must finally be given and explained from Greek to Roman: Catholic means one, or as the more learned believe, obedience to all, namely to the commandments of God.

119
00:11:03,779 --> 00:11:07,986
Hence the Apostle: If you are obedient in all things (Second Corinthians 2:9).

120
00:11:07,986 --> 00:11:15,483
And again: For as by the disobedience of one many were made sinners, so by the obedience of one, many will be made righteous (Romans 5:19).

121
00:11:15,483 --> 00:11:18,935
Therefore, he who is Catholic is also obedient to the righteous.

122
00:11:18,935 --> 00:11:22,818
He who is obedient is also a Christian: thus, a Catholic is a Christian.

123
00:11:22,818 --> 00:11:26,647
Therefore, our people are separated from heretics by the name Catholic.

124
00:11:26,647 --> 00:11:37,110
Additionally, if Catholic means one everywhere, as the superior ones think, David indicates the same saying: The queen stood in a golden vestment and adorned (Psalms 45:10), that is, one in all.

125
00:11:37,110 --> 00:11:46,441
And in the Song of Songs, the Groom says: My dove is one, my perfect one, she is the only one of her mother, she is the chosen one of her who bore her (Song of Solomon 6:8).

126
00:11:46,441 --> 00:11:50,324
And again: Virgins will be brought to the king after her (Psalms 45:15).

127
00:11:50,324 --> 00:11:53,668
And still: Young maidens without number (Song of Solomon 6:7).

128
00:11:53,668 --> 00:11:56,257
Therefore, in all things one, and one above all.

129
00:11:57,552 --> 00:12:01,511
But don't worry, brother: Christian is my name, and Catholic is my surname.

130
00:12:01,511 --> 00:12:04,098
The first identifies me; the second describes me.

131
00:12:04,098 --> 00:12:07,002
This is how I am known, and that is how I am signified.

132
00:12:07,002 --> 00:12:17,087
If we need to explain the meaning of the word Catholic and translate it from Greek into Latin: Catholic means 'universal', or, as the more educated think, 'obedient to all God's commandments.

133
00:12:17,087 --> 00:13:38,817
' Hence the Apostle says, "If you are obedient in everything" Second Corinthians 2:9. And again: "For just as through the disobedience of one man many were made sinners, so also through the obedience of one man many will be made righteous" Romans 5:19.
Therefore, a Catholic is also obedient to righteousness. Whoever is obedient is also a Christian: thus, a Catholic is a Christian. This is why our people are distinguished from heretics by this name, Catholic: and if Catholic means 'one everywhere,' as the elders think, David also indicates this when he says, "The queen stood in gold from Ophir" Psalm 45:9, that is, one in all things.
In the Song of Songs, the Bridegroom says: "My dove, my perfect one, is unique, the only daughter of her mother, chosen by the one who bore her" Song of Solomon 6:9. And again: "They will be led to the king, the virgins, her companions who follow her" Psalm 45:14.
And also: "The maidens, without number" Song of Solomon 6:8. Therefore, she is one in all things and one above all. If you seek the reason for the name, it is clear.
As for repentance, may God grant that it is never necessary for the faithful; may no one fall into the pit of death after the help of the holy font: nor should priests be forced to offer late consolations or teach them, lest they open the way to sin while comforting the sinner with remedies. But we reveal this indulgence of our God to the wretched, not to the blessed, not before sin, but after sins are revealed: and we announce healing not to the healthy, but to the sick.

134
00:13:38,975 --> 00:13:49,641
If spiritual evils have no power over the baptized, then neither does the deceit of that serpent which first led humanity astray and imposed so many titles of damnation on its descendants.

135
00:13:49,641 --> 00:13:58,661
If it has retreated from the world, if we have already begun to reign, if no sin sneaks into our eyes, hands, or minds, then let this gift of God be discarded.

136
00:13:58,661 --> 00:14:04,221
Let help be rejected, let no confession, no groans be heard; let proud justice scorn every remedy.

137
00:14:04,221 --> 00:14:13,241
But if the Lord has provided this for His people, if He has granted rewards to those who stand and remedies to those who fall, then stop accusing divine mercy.

138
00:14:13,241 --> 00:14:20,843
Stop erasing so many titles of heavenly clemency with rigorous objections, or denying the Lord’s free gifts with unyielding harshness.

139
00:14:20,843 --> 00:14:23,793
We do not grant these things from our own resources.

140
00:14:23,793 --> 00:14:28,729
Turn to me, says the Lord, along with fasting, weeping, and mourning; tear your hearts.

141
00:14:28,729 --> 00:14:29,296
Joel 2:12.

142
00:14:29,296 --> 00:14:37,466
And again: Let the wicked forsake his ways, and the unrighteous man his thoughts, and let him return to the Lord, and He will have mercy on him.

143
00:14:37,466 --> 00:14:38,146
Isaiah 55:7.

144
00:14:38,146 --> 00:14:45,578
Likewise, the Prophet cries out in this way: Because God is gracious, and merciful, patient, and who relents from sending calamity.

145
00:14:45,578 --> 00:14:46,145
Joel 2:13.

146
00:14:46,145 --> 00:14:50,457
Does the serpent have such lasting venom, and Christ does not have a remedy?

147
00:14:50,457 --> 00:14:53,747
The devil kills in the world, and Christ cannot help here?

148
00:14:53,747 --> 00:14:57,889
Certainly, let it be painful to sin, but let it not be painful to repent.

149
00:14:57,889 --> 00:15:01,803
Let it be shameful to be in danger, but not shameful to be delivered.

150
00:15:01,803 --> 00:15:06,228
Who would take away a plank from a shipwrecked person to prevent their escape?

151
00:15:06,228 --> 00:15:08,554
Who would begrudge the healing of wounds?

152
00:15:08,554 --> 00:15:13,830
Does not David say: I drench my bed with my tears every night; I flood my couch with weeping.

153
00:15:13,830 --> 00:15:14,398
Psalm 6:6.

154
00:15:14,398 --> 00:15:18,028
And again: I acknowledge my sin; I did not cover up my iniquity.

155
00:15:18,028 --> 00:15:18,653
Psalm 32:5.

156
00:15:18,653 --> 00:15:38,111
And further: I said, "I will confess my transgressions to the Lord," and you forgave the guilt of my sin.
Did not the prophet respond to David after his guilt of murder and adultery, for Bathsheba’s repentance: The Lord has taken away your sin.
Second Samuel 12:13.
Did not confession free the Babylonian king after so many crimes of idolatry?

157
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:45,257
And what does the Lord say: "Does not one who falls get up, and the one who turns away come back?" (Jeremiah 8:4).

158
00:15:45,257 --> 00:15:48,516
What do those many examples of the Lord's arguments respond to?

159
00:15:48,516 --> 00:16:02,793
The woman who finds the lost coin and rejoices; the shepherd who brings back the wandering sheep; the father who warmly welcomes his returning son, after he squandered all his wealth and lived with prostitutes and sinners, and who scolds the jealous brother by showing reason?

160
00:16:02,793 --> 00:16:08,018
Saying, "This son of mine was dead and has come back to life; he was lost and is found" (Luke 15:32).

161
00:16:08,018 --> 00:16:12,002
What about the man injured on the road, ignored by the Levite and the priest?

162
00:16:12,002 --> 00:16:13,140
Doesn’t he get healed?

163
00:16:13,140 --> 00:16:30,625
Consider what the Spirit says to the churches (Revelation 2):
He accuses the Ephesians of abandoned love; charges the Thyatirans with adultery; criticizes the Sardians for halting their work, and the Pergamenes for teaching different doctrines; rebukes the Laodiceans for their wealth; and yet invites all to repentance with satisfaction.

164
00:16:30,625 --> 00:16:43,299
What does the Apostle say to the Corinthians: "Lest, when I come, I should mourn over many of those who have sinned before and have not repented of the uncleanness, fornication, and lewdness which they have practiced" (Second Corinthians 12:21).

165
00:16:43,299 --> 00:16:54,783
And again to the Galatians: "If anyone is caught in any transgression" (Galatians 6:1); that is, in any, you who are spiritual should restore such a one in a spirit of gentleness, watching yourself lest you too be tempted.

166
00:16:54,783 --> 00:16:59,025
Does the head of the household in a large house keep only silver and gold vessels?

167
00:16:59,025 --> 00:17:03,422
Does he not also honor clay and wooden ones, and some that are repaired and restored?

168
00:17:03,422 --> 00:17:08,802
Now I rejoice, says the Apostle, because you were made sorrowful to repentance (Second Corinthians 7:9).

169
00:17:08,802 --> 00:17:14,906
And again: "For godly sorrow produces repentance leading to salvation, not to be regretted" (Second Corinthians 7:10).

170
00:17:14,906 --> 00:17:17,596
If you seek the reason for the name, it is apparent.

171
00:17:17,596 --> 00:17:33,115
As for repentance, may God grant that it is not necessary for any of the faithful; may no one after the help of the sacred font fall into the pit of death; nor should priests be forced to offer late consolations or teach them, lest they open the way to sin while they soothe the sinner with remedies.

172
00:17:33,839 --> 00:17:39,165
We reveal God's mercy not to the blessed, but to the wretched, not before sin, but to expose sins.

173
00:17:39,165 --> 00:17:42,752
We announce medicine not to the healthy, but to those who are ill.

174
00:17:42,752 --> 00:18:04,599
If spiritual wickedness has no power over the baptized, if the serpent's deceit—which first overthrew man and marked his descendants with so many titles of damnation—can do nothing, if it has retreated from the world, if we have already begun to reign, if no crime enters our eyes, hands, or minds, then let this gift of God be rejected, let the help be repelled, let no confession, no groans be heard.

175
00:18:04,599 --> 00:18:06,718
Let proud justice despise every remedy.

176
00:18:06,718 --> 00:18:23,185
But if the Lord has provided these things for His own; if He has given rewards to those who stand and remedies to those who fall, stop accusing divine mercy or erasing the many titles of heavenly clemency by the objection of severity, or prohibiting the free gifts of the Lord with unyielding harshness.

177
00:18:23,185 --> 00:18:25,141
We do not bestow these from our own.

178
00:18:25,141 --> 00:18:30,739
"Turn to me," says the Lord, "with fasting and weeping and mourning, and rend your hearts" (Joel 2:12).

179
00:18:30,739 --> 00:18:39,217
And again: "Let the wicked forsake their ways and the unrighteous their thoughts, and let them turn to the Lord, and they will receive mercy" (Isaiah 45:7).

180
00:18:39,217 --> 00:18:48,075
Similarly, the Prophet cries out: "For God is gracious and merciful, slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love, and relents from sending calamity" (Joel 2:13).

181
00:18:48,075 --> 00:18:51,988
Does the serpent have such enduring venom, and Christ not have medicine?

182
00:18:51,988 --> 00:18:55,357
Does the devil kill in the world, and Christ cannot help here?

183
00:18:55,357 --> 00:18:58,781
Certainly, let it be painful to sin, but not painful to repent.

184
00:18:58,781 --> 00:19:02,313
Let it be shameful to be in danger, but not shameful to be saved.

185
00:19:02,313 --> 00:19:06,715
Who would snatch a plank from a shipwreck survivor to prevent them from escaping?

186
00:19:06,715 --> 00:19:08,563
Who would begrudge healing wounds?

187
00:19:08,563 --> 00:19:14,215
Does not David say, "Every night I flood my bed with tears; I drench my couch with weeping" (Psalm 6:6)?

188
00:19:14,215 --> 00:19:18,943
And again, "I acknowledge my sin to you and did not cover up my iniquity" (Psalm 32:5).

189
00:19:18,943 --> 00:19:25,356
And still, "I said, 'I will confess my transgressions to the Lord,' and you forgave the guilt of my sin" (Psalm 32:5).

190
00:19:26,279 --> 00:21:18,240
Didn't the prophet respond after David was guilty of murder and adultery, and repented for Bathsheba: "The Lord has taken away your sin" 2 Samuel 12:13?
Didn't repentance free the Babylonian king after so many acts of idolatry condemned him? And what does the Lord mean when He says: "Doesn't the one who falls rise again, and the one who turns away return" Jeremiah 8:4?
What do all those parables of the Lord mean? That the woman finds the lost coin and rejoices; that the shepherd brings back the wandering sheep; that the father lovingly meets the returning son after he squandered all his wealth with prostitutes and sinners, and reproves the envious brother? The father says, "This son of mine was dead and is alive again; he was lost and is found" Luke 15:32.
What about the man who was wounded on the road, and passed by the Levite and the priest? Isn't he healed?
Consider what the Spirit says to the churches: He accuses the Ephesians of abandoned love; charges the Thyatirans with adultery; rebukes the Sardians for their incomplete works, the Pergamenes for teaching false doctrines; scorches the Laodiceans for their wealth; yet invites all to repentance through atonement.
What does the Apostle say to the Corinthians? "I fear that when I come, I may grieve over many who have sinned earlier and have not repented of the impurity, sexual immorality, and debauchery they have committed" 2 Corinthians 12:21.
And again to the Galatians? "If someone is caught in a sin, you who live by the Spirit should restore that person gently, but watch yourselves, or you also may be tempted" Galatians 6:1.
Does the master of a great house keep only silver and gold vessels? Doesn't he also keep vessels of clay and wood, some for special purposes and some for common use?
Now I rejoice, says the Apostle, not because you were made sorrowful, but because your sorrow led you to repentance 2 Corinthians 7:9. And again: "Godly sorrow brings repentance that leads to salvation and leaves no regret" 2 Corinthians 7:10.
But one could not repent. No one commands labor without reward: "The worker is worthy of his wages" Matthew 10:10; Luke 10:7.

191
00:21:18,240 --> 00:21:22,349
God would never threaten someone who repents unless He intended to forgive them.

192
00:21:22,349 --> 00:21:37,349
You might say, "Only God can do this." That's true: but what He does through His priests is still His power. What did He mean when He told the Apostles:
"Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven" (Matthew 16:19; John 20:23)?

193
00:21:37,349 --> 00:21:41,099
Why would He say this if it weren't allowed for people to bind and loose?

194
00:21:41,099 --> 00:21:43,205
Is this permission only for the Apostles?

195
00:21:43,205 --> 00:21:51,270
If only they can baptize, give the Holy Spirit, and cleanse the sins of the nations, because all this was commanded only to the Apostles, then what about us?

196
00:21:51,270 --> 00:22:02,571
If in one place the power to release bonds and perform the sacraments is given, either everything has been passed down to us through the example and power of the Apostles, or none of it has been relaxed from the decrees.

197
00:22:02,571 --> 00:22:07,246
"I laid the foundation," he says, "and someone else builds on it" (First Corinthians 3:10).

198
00:22:07,246 --> 00:22:10,637
So, we build on what the doctrine of the Apostles has established.

199
00:22:10,637 --> 00:22:17,777
Finally, bishops are also called Apostles, as Paul explains about Epaphroditus:
"My brother and coworker; your apostle" (Philippians 2:25).

200
00:22:17,777 --> 00:22:25,585
Therefore, if the power of baptism and chrism, and the greater and long-standing gifts come down to bishops, they also have the right to bind and loose.

201
00:22:25,585 --> 00:22:32,725
Even if we claim this right recklessly because of our sins, God will not deny it to those who hold the seat of the Apostles and the saints.

202
00:22:32,725 --> 00:22:35,448
He has even granted bishops the name of His Only Son.

203
00:22:35,448 --> 00:22:37,143
But it was not allowed to repent.

204
00:22:37,143 --> 00:22:42,126
No one orders labor without a reward: "The worker deserves his wages" (Matthew 10:10; Luke 10:7).

205
00:22:42,126 --> 00:22:46,236
God would never threaten someone who repents unless He intended to forgive them.

206
00:22:46,236 --> 00:23:01,236
You might say, "Only God can do this." That's true: but what He does through His priests is still His power. What did He mean when He told the Apostles:
"Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven" (Matthew 16:19; John 20:23)?

207
00:23:01,236 --> 00:23:04,986
