229
00:26:35,587 --> 00:26:37,916
All of it has flowed from apostolic authority.

230
00:26:37,916 --> 00:26:47,283
I know, brother, that this very pardon for repentance is not given to everyone everywhere, nor is it relaxed before either an interpretation of divine will or a visitation has occurred.

231
00:26:48,144 --> 00:26:54,792
With deep reflection and heavy hearts, after many sighs and tears, and the prayers of the entire church, true repentance cannot be denied.

232
00:26:54,792 --> 00:26:56,960
No one should judge before Christ's judgment.

233
00:26:56,960 --> 00:27:01,151
If you express your thoughts more clearly, brother, you will gain better understanding.

234
00:27:01,248 --> 00:27:04,895
Letter TwoAbout Sympronian's letters.

235
00:27:04,895 --> 00:27:08,100
Pacianus the bishop sends greetings to his brother Sympronian. I.

236
00:27:08,100 --> 00:27:11,009
In this lengthy discussion, I will be as brief as possible.

237
00:27:11,009 --> 00:27:15,890
I won't repay you, brother, with malice for your hidden verbal attacks disguised as good questions.

238
00:27:15,890 --> 00:27:27,327
We are commanded to pray for those who persecute us and to bless those who curse us (Matthew 5:44)
Deceit is like a fox, while force is like a lion: both are very uncharacteristic of a person; but deceit is more deserving of hatred.

239
00:27:27,327 --> 00:27:34,427
When you think you can cause more harm, you ask questions as if you are ignorant; when you believe you are teaching, you pretend to be learning.

240
00:27:34,427 --> 00:27:51,041
The old Pharisees called the Lord "Rabbi" when they posed riddles from the law; they called Him "Master" when they claimed all authority for themselves. Whatever you do, brother, you will learn everything from me plainly. I prefer to be understood as unskilled rather than malicious; I prefer to be judged as foolish rather than cunning.

241
00:27:51,288 --> 00:27:58,567
So, before I explain the reasoning behind our faith—which is what you're asking about—let me address a few points from your letter that you prioritized.

242
00:27:58,567 --> 00:28:04,075
You mentioned that my previous letters have restored you, yet you immediately add that I responded with bitterness.

243
00:28:04,075 --> 00:28:10,924
If bitter things restore, I wonder what sweet things would do; perhaps, like in medicinal drinks, the bitter tends to heal more than the sweet.

244
00:28:10,924 --> 00:28:15,761
But I ask you to reread my letters to see if they contained any bitterness, pride, or unpleasantness.

245
00:28:15,761 --> 00:28:18,539
You say I mentioned many heresies that no one asked about.

246
00:28:18,539 --> 00:28:21,365
Well, what does it matter to you if you were not a heretic?

247
00:28:21,365 --> 00:28:30,895
Since you questioned our faith and said you wanted to be taught, I noted that ignorance has many causes and asked you to clarify which one applies to you, so I wouldn't have to cover too many points.

248
00:28:30,895 --> 00:28:35,972
I responded calmly about the Catholic name, explaining that it doesn't matter what someone else is called.

249
00:28:35,972 --> 00:28:45,982
And if you seek the significance of the name—whether it is something marvelous, unique, or above all—or, as I haven't said before, related to the Christian people, know that it wasn't given to us to fade away.

250
00:28:45,982 --> 00:28:50,292
Indeed, I am glad that although you prefer others, you still agree with us about the name.

251
00:28:50,292 --> 00:28:52,352
If you denied it, nature would proclaim it.

252
00:28:52,352 --> 00:28:54,746
And if you still have doubts, let's remain silent.

253
00:28:54,746 --> 00:28:58,386
Whatever we are called, we will be, as shown by the name's enduring history.

254
00:28:58,386 --> 00:29:05,139
