00:34:06,352 --> 00:34:10,750
' And how do you think this comes from a verse of Virgil if you didn’t know Virgil at all?

313
00:34:10,750 --> 00:34:12,899
But I deny that I quoted the verse in order.

314
00:34:12,899 --> 00:34:18,323
For I said: 'Those whom obscure fame hides;' as is customary in human speech, to say something previously said.

315
00:34:18,323 --> 00:34:21,303
But you repeated the verse in its proper order and structure.

316
00:34:21,303 --> 00:34:25,065
Did you love Virgil so much that you thought it wrong if you broke his verse?

317
00:34:25,065 --> 00:34:26,873
And yet, I learned it from childhood.

318
00:34:26,873 --> 00:34:29,218
Is it surprising if I stumbled upon what I knew?

319
00:34:29,218 --> 00:34:33,957
In you, brother, there’s such effort that you now read what you once blushed to read from others?

320
00:34:33,957 --> 00:34:41,970
Should you accuse a Latin speaker for speaking Latin, as much as a Greek for speaking Greek, a Parthian for speaking Parthian, a Phoenician for speaking Phoenician?

321
00:34:41,970 --> 00:34:48,419
The Medes, Egyptians, and Hebrews have their own language according to the abundance of the Lord, who modulated it into 120 tongues.

322
00:34:48,419 --> 00:34:49,934
A bishop quoted a poetic verse.

323
00:34:49,934 --> 00:34:51,302
What about the Apostle Paul?

324
00:34:51,302 --> 00:34:54,575
Does he blush when he both quotes and approves that Athenian verse?

325
00:34:55,943 --> 00:35:01,453
In the Acts of the Apostles, it says:
Some of your own poets have said:
For we are also his offspring.

326
00:35:01,453 --> 00:35:03,992
Since we are God's offspring
(Acts 17:28, 29)
.

327
00:35:03,992 --> 00:35:11,825
And again, he said to Titus:
One of them, a prophet of their own, said,
'Cretans are always liars, evil beasts, lazy gluttons'
(Titus 1:12, 13)
.

328
00:35:11,825 --> 00:35:13,770
And he adds:
This testimony is true.

329
00:35:13,770 --> 00:35:19,550
We sin by example:
We are not rhetoricians, but we believe in any voice that comes as the abundance of God.

330
00:35:19,550 --> 00:35:24,790
Rome, Egypt, Athens, Thrace, Arabs, Spain confess God; the Holy Spirit understands all languages.

331
00:35:24,790 --> 00:35:52,394
Why do you say,
"I will polish your writings with lively cedar against the decayed enemies of the Muses"?
Which Muses, I pray, are you talking about?
Are they the ones who invented letters and wrote pages that moths will pursue?
Tell me, brother, did the Muses discover letters?
Is not everything through the Lord, and everything from God?
Besides those 120 languages, was there another of the Muses?
Hesiod lied about that on Helicon, but the Athenians, as the Apostle said, did nothing but talk
(Acts 17:21)
.

332
00:35:52,394 --> 00:35:59,470
We, as the Apostle testifies
(First Corinthians 14:10, 18)
,
retain all kinds of voices and all kinds of languages inspired by God.

333
00:35:59,470 --> 00:36:09,896
However, I forgive you, brother, if you presume something from your author and combine the philosophy of Novatian, through which he suffered shipwreck in religion, with the authority of Hesiod.

334
00:36:09,896 --> 00:36:17,783
Nevertheless, you should have remembered the Apostle who said:
Beware lest anyone cheat you through philosophy and empty deceit
(Colossians 2:8)
.

335
00:36:17,783 --> 00:36:19,673
What are you criticizing and doing?

336
00:36:19,673 --> 00:36:25,021
Are we coming to a rhetorician, or is it an art to be handled, or am I explaining verses of Virgil?

337
00:36:25,021 --> 00:36:29,235
When I mentioned several heretics, I added:
And those whom obscure fame hides.

338
00:36:29,235 --> 00:36:34,259
And how do you think this was taken from a verse of Virgil if you did not know Virgil at all?

339
00:36:34,259 --> 00:36:36,960
But I deny it; I did not place the verse in order.

340
00:36:36,960 --> 00:36:45,224
For I said:
Those whom obscure fame hides;
as it is customary for speakers to say something from the abundance of human speech that has been said before.

341
00:36:45,224 --> 00:36:48,141
But you repeated the verse in its order and structure.

342
00:36:48,141 --> 00:36:52,841
You loved Virgil so much that you thought it would not be right if you broke his verse?

343
00:36:53,759 --> 00:36:57,800
I learned this from a young age. Is it any wonder I fell into what I knew?

344
00:36:57,800 --> 00:37:02,987
Brother, you put in so much effort, only to now read what you once blushed to read from others?

345
00:37:02,987 --> 00:37:12,269
If you were educated in Latin and speak Latin, should you not criticize just as you would a Greek speaking Greek, a Parthian speaking Parthian, or a Punic speaking Punic?

346
00:37:12,269 --> 00:37:20,296
Medes, Egyptians, Hebrews all have their own languages, according to the abundance of the Lord, who expressed it in one hundred and twenty tongues.

347
00:37:20,296 --> 00:37:22,098
The bishop quoted a poetic verse.

348
00:37:22,098 --> 00:37:23,627
What about the Apostle Paul?

349
00:37:23,627 --> 00:37:27,012
Did he blush when he recited and approved that Athenian verse?

350
00:37:27,012 --> 00:37:35,803
For in the Acts of the Apostles, it is written: "Some of your own poets have said, 'For we are indeed his offspring.'" So being God's offspring (Acts 17:28, 29).

351
00:37:35,803 --> 00:37:44,048
And he also said to Titus: "One of themselves, a prophet of their own, said, 'Cretans are always liars, evil beasts, lazy gluttons.'" (Titus 1:12, 13).

352
00:37:44,048 --> 00:38:27,565
And he adds: "This testimony is true."
So we sin by example: we are not rhetoricians, but we believe in whatever voice, the abundance of God.
Latium, Egypt, Athens, Thrace, Arabs, Spaniards all confess God; the Holy Spirit understands all languages.
Why do you say, "I will preserve your letters with durable cedar against the decayed enemies of the Muses?"
Which Muses, I ask?
Are they the ones who discovered letters and wrote papers that moths will pursue?
Tell me, brother, did the Muses discover letters?
Is not everything through the Lord, and everything from God?
Besides those one hundred and twenty languages, was there another of the Muses?
Hesiod lied about this on Helicon, with the enthusiasm of the Athenians, who, as the Apostle said, had no interest except in talking (Acts 17:21).

353
00:38:27,565 --> 00:38:34,882
We, with the Apostle as our witness (First Corinthians 14:10, 18), retain all modes of speech, all kinds of languages inspired by God.

354
00:38:34,882 --> 00:38:45,311
I forgive you, brother, if you presume anything from your author, and if you combine Novatian's philosophy, through which he fell into the shipwreck of religion, with the authority of Hesiod.

355
00:38:45,311 --> 00:38:53,992
Nevertheless, you should have remembered the Apostle, who said: "See to it that no one takes you captive through philosophy and empty deceit" (Colossians 2:8).

356
00:38:54,647 --> 00:38:57,660
Now, what do you think of this accusation against Catholics?

357
00:38:57,660 --> 00:39:05,996
If kings or empires have ever persecuted you,
by the same logic, should it not be held against you whenever Catholics have endured persecution from kings and empires?

358
00:39:05,996 --> 00:39:08,155
Our people were persecuted by pagan rulers.

359
00:39:08,155 --> 00:39:10,164
Did you endure the hatred of Christians?

360
00:39:10,164 --> 00:39:11,720
But our people complained more.

361
00:39:11,720 --> 00:39:17,194
Let the one who did this see with what intention and spirit it was done;
whether it was for peace or discord.

362
00:39:17,194 --> 00:39:22,617
Even if some of them did wrong, as it is written,
Does their unfaithfulness nullify the faithfulness of God?

363
00:39:22,617 --> 00:39:23,270
(Romans 3:3).

364
00:39:23,270 --> 00:39:26,383
However, do not think that our people were merely complaining.

365
00:39:26,383 --> 00:39:34,116
When Christian rulers began to emerge through our faith,
those rulers, favoring the Catholic side, that is, their own side, were moved by their own grief.

366
00:39:34,116 --> 00:39:49,682
Unless perhaps it will be held against Daniel that he was vindicated by Darius,
or against the most holy woman Esther, when the king's leader was killed for her sake,
or against the three youths, because the Babylonian king threatened the profane and unbelieving because of them after the trials of the flames.

367
00:39:49,682 --> 00:39:52,494
Did not Peter confound Simon, with the judge's approval?

368
00:39:52,494 --> 00:39:55,005
Did not Paul blind Elymas, with Sergius's support?

369
00:39:55,005 --> 00:39:59,123
And he would have been vindicated in Jerusalem, if he had any faith to hold on to.

370
00:39:59,123 --> 00:40:04,245
Do you not know that the authorities serve the innocent and minister for the good of the holy fathers?

371
00:40:04,245 --> 00:40:07,860
As the Apostle says: Rulers are not a terror to good works, but to evil.

372
00:40:07,860 --> 00:40:10,069
Do you want to be unafraid of the authority?

373
00:40:10,069 --> 00:40:15,744
Do what is good, and you will have praise from the same; for he is God's servant to you for good
(Romans 13:3-4).

374
00:40:15,744 --> 00:40:19,459
And yet I have complained about no one, nor have I been avenged by anyone.

375
00:40:19,459 --> 00:40:25,435
I do not think the Novatians are a hindrance to me, whose small number and weakness I could boast about if I wanted to.

376
00:40:25,435 --> 00:40:29,101
Behold, no one accuses your people before the Emperor, and you are alone.

377
00:40:29,101 --> 00:40:33,620
We all must stand before the judgment seat of God
(Romans 14:10; Second Corinthians 5:19).

378
00:40:33,620 --> 00:40:38,039
One thing I know, the Novatians would complain if their cause was favored by any rulers.

379
00:40:39,143 --> 00:40:42,755
You endured the hatred of Christians? But our people complained more.

380
00:40:42,755 --> 00:40:47,781
Let the one who did this see with what intention and spirit; whether he sought peace or discord.

381
00:40:47,781 --> 00:40:53,016
But even if some of them sinned, he says, does their unfaithfulness nullify the faithfulness of God?

382
00:40:53,016 --> 00:40:56,785
(Romans 3:3)
Yet, you should not think that our people were complaining.

383
00:40:56,785 --> 00:41:04,951
When Christian leaders began to emerge from our faith, those very leaders, favoring the Catholic Church—that is, their own side—were moved by personal pain.

384
00:41:04,951 --> 00:41:19,347
Unless perhaps Daniel is to be blamed for being avenged by Darius, or Esther, the most holy woman, when the leader of the king was killed for her; or the three boys, because for them, after the ordeal of the flames, the Babylonian king threatened the impious and unbelieving.

385
00:41:19,347 --> 00:41:22,173
Did not Peter confound Simon, with the judge agreeing?

386
00:41:22,173 --> 00:41:24,791
Did not Paul blind Elymas, with Sergius approving?

387
00:41:24,791 --> 00:41:28,612
He would also have been avenged in Jerusalem if he had any binding faith.

388
00:41:28,612 --> 00:41:33,480
Do you not know that powers serve the innocent and minister for the good of the holy fathers?

389
00:41:33,480 --> 00:41:37,354
As the Apostle says: Leaders are not a terror to good conduct, but to bad.

390
00:41:37,354 --> 00:41:39,500
Do you wish to have no fear of authority?

391
00:41:39,500 --> 00:41:45,311
Do what is good, and you will receive approval from it through the Lord: For he is God's servant for your good.

392
00:41:45,311 --> 00:41:49,761
(Romans 13:3-4)
And yet I did not complain about anyone, nor was I avenged by anyone.

393
00:41:49,761 --> 00:41:55,623
Nor do I think that the Novatians hinder me, whose insignificance and shortcomings I could boast of if I wished.

394
00:41:55,623 --> 00:41:59,235
Behold, no one accuses your people to the emperor, and you are alone.

395
00:41:59,235 --> 00:42:01,853
We all must stand before the judgment seat of God.

396
00:42:01,853 --> 00:42:08,972
(Romans 14:10; Second Corinthians 5:19) This one thing I know, the Novatians would complain if their cause were pleasing to any princes.

397
00:42:08,972 --> 00:42:11,485
You say it is more useful to win than to please.

398
00:42:11,485 --> 00:42:15,306
But those who are driven by the desire to win advance through contention.

399
00:42:15,306 --> 00:42:21,274
The Apostle, however, says: If anyone seems to be contentious, we have no such custom, nor do the churches of God.

400
00:42:21,274 --> 00:42:30,958
(First Corinthians 9:16) On the contrary, regarding the desire to please: I try to please everyone in everything, not seeking my own advantage, but that of many, that they may be saved.

401
00:42:30,958 --> 00:42:39,648
(First Corinthians 10:33) But you, while thinking of your own interests and not those of your brothers, prefer to crush by winning rather than to restore by pleasing.

402
00:42:40,799 --> 00:42:47,327
To overcome evil with good is rational; however, in any situation, wanting to be victorious is a sign of irrational arrogance.

403
00:42:47,327 --> 00:42:55,253
This perspective is not from Apostolic law but from Greek tradition, where it is believed that the entire Spartan custom was driven by the desire to win.

404
00:42:55,253 --> 00:43:00,019
The muddy pig and the insane tiger, what else do they want but to win rather than to please?

405
00:43:00,019 --> 00:43:03,904
You write that you have free time, and thus contentious things delight you.

406
00:43:03,904 --> 00:43:10,794
As for me, occupied with Catholic affairs, your letters were delivered to me after almost 30 days and repeated after another 40 days.

407
00:43:10,794 --> 00:43:13,695
It would be more useful, you say, to win than to please.

408
00:43:13,695 --> 00:43:17,736
But those who are driven by the fervor of winning progress through contention.

409
00:43:17,736 --> 00:43:25,196
However, the Apostle says: "But if anyone seems to be contentious, we have no such custom, nor does the Church of God" (First Corinthians 9:16).

410
00:43:25,196 --> 00:43:34,676
On the contrary, regarding the effort to please: "I please all men in all things, not seeking my own profit, but the profit of many, that they may be saved" (First Corinthians 10:33).

411
00:43:34,676 --> 00:43:41,825
But you, considering your own advantages rather than those of your brothers, prefer to crush by winning rather than to revive by pleasing.

412
00:43:41,825 --> 00:43:48,352
To overcome evil with good is rational; however, in any situation, wanting to be victorious is a sign of irrational arrogance.

413
00:43:48,352 --> 00:43:56,278
This perspective is not from Apostolic law but from Greek tradition, where it is believed that the entire Spartan custom was driven by the desire to win.

414
00:43:56,278 --> 00:44:01,044
The muddy pig and the insane tiger, what else do they want but to win rather than to please?

415
00:44:01,044 --> 00:44:04,930
You write that you have free time, and thus contentious things delight you.

416
00:44:04,930 --> 00:44:11,820
As for me, occupied with Catholic affairs, your letters were delivered to me after almost 30 days and repeated after another 40 days.

417
00:44:11,820 --> 00:44:13,736
You say that I am angry; far from it.

418
00:44:13,736 --> 00:44:17,414
I am stirred, like a bee that sometimes defends its honey with a sting.

419
00:44:17,414 --> 00:44:22,232
But consider both of our letters; you will see whether we arm our page with barbs or flowers.

420
00:44:22,232 --> 00:44:26,066
As for those like you, the Apostle says they must be stopped (Titus 1:11).

421
00:44:26,066 --> 00:44:26,998
But pay attention.

422
00:44:26,998 --> 00:44:30,314
We contend with you like doves, more with words than with teeth.

423
00:44:30,314 --> 00:44:32,956
Would that it were true that you wish to be taught!

424
00:44:32,956 --> 00:44:36,945
I would already be offering you the holy oil of the Spirit with my own hands.

425
00:44:36,945 --> 00:44:37,722
Do you love me?

426
00:44:37,722 --> 00:44:39,172
I have not hurt you, I know.

427
00:44:40,415 --> 00:44:45,918
Only then can you truly love, if you approach my work with kindness and without holding differing opinions.

428
00:44:45,918 --> 00:44:48,746
You're curious why I appreciate the letters of Cyprian?

429
00:44:48,746 --> 00:44:52,089
Why not, given that he is a blessed martyr and a Catholic priest?

430
00:44:52,089 --> 00:44:53,477
You mention Novatian to me?

431
00:44:53,477 --> 00:44:58,774
I know he was a worldly philosopher, and it's no surprise he strayed from the Church of the living God.

432
00:44:58,774 --> 00:45:03,608
He abandoned the ancient law and the heritage of the old people out of envy towards Cornelius.

433
00:45:03,608 --> 00:45:08,133
He supported the madness of Novatus and became a bishop without legitimate consecration.

434
00:45:08,133 --> 00:45:14,818
Thus, he was never truly made one, even with a letter from those pretending to be Confessors, who sought to divide the one mother.

435
00:45:14,818 --> 00:45:19,189
I'll prove these points to you, brother, through the writings of your own Confessors.

436
00:45:19,189 --> 00:45:25,411
Your philosopher, trying to establish his own wisdom, as the Apostle says in Romans 10:3, is not subject to God's wisdom.

437
00:45:25,411 --> 00:45:28,342
The world did not recognize God's wisdom through its own.

438
00:45:28,342 --> 00:45:31,788
You think Novatian suffered, and you add that Cyprian mentioned it.

439
00:45:31,788 --> 00:45:34,462
My adversary preceded me; see how clearly I respond.

440
00:45:34,462 --> 00:45:40,324
Novatian never endured martyrdom, nor has this ever been heard or read from the words of the most blessed Cyprian.

441
00:45:40,324 --> 00:45:45,158
Cyprian's letters report Cornelius, the bishop of the city, whom Novatian envied at that time.

442
00:45:45,158 --> 00:45:49,220
Cornelius resisted enemy leaders, often confessed, and was frequently harassed.

443
00:45:49,220 --> 00:45:56,574
He was made a leader by many Confessors and Martyrs and was crowned most gloriously with many others while Novatian was still alive and secure.

444
00:45:56,574 --> 00:46:00,534
Indeed, Novatian left the church of Christ to avoid the burden of confession.

445
00:46:00,534 --> 00:46:03,413
Driven by envy, he couldn't bear Cornelius's episcopate.

446
00:46:03,413 --> 00:46:06,499
Ridiculed by a few letters, he committed himself to Novatus.

447
00:46:06,499 --> 00:46:09,841
Cyprian's letters will teach you all these things about Novatian.

448
00:46:09,841 --> 00:46:14,572
Even if Novatian did suffer, he wasn't killed; and even if he was killed, he wasn't crowned.

449
00:46:14,572 --> 00:46:14,984
Why not?

450
00:46:14,984 --> 00:46:20,434
Because outside the peace of the Church, outside concord, outside the mother, one cannot be a true martyr.

451
00:46:20,434 --> 00:46:26,245
Listen to the Apostle: And if I have all faith, so as to remove mountains; but do not have charity, I am nothing.

452
00:46:27,479 --> 00:46:34,536
And if I give away all my possessions to feed the poor, and if I surrender my body to be burned, but do not have love, it profits me nothing.

453
00:46:34,536 --> 00:46:35,787
First Corinthians 13:2-3.

454
00:46:35,787 --> 00:46:43,343
As for Cyprian, he suffered in harmony with everyone, in common peace, among the group of Confessors, and often confessed during repeated persecutions.

455
00:46:43,343 --> 00:46:47,447
He was tormented with many lacerations and was finally offered the saving chalice.

456
00:46:47,447 --> 00:46:48,898
This was his crowning moment.

457
00:46:48,898 --> 00:46:55,904
Therefore, let Novatian keep his letters to himself; let him keep his arrogance and pride, which, while lifting him up, caused his downfall.

458
00:46:55,904 --> 00:46:57,856
While sparing no one, he was scattered.

459
00:46:57,856 --> 00:47:02,510
Behold the one who blocks the path of salvation for his brothers with unyielding religiosity!

460
00:47:02,510 --> 00:47:07,614
Behold the one who confidently claims to bear himself openly and to purify the Lord’s threshing floor!

461
00:47:07,614 --> 00:47:09,216
You say I am angry; far from it.

462
00:47:09,216 --> 00:47:12,719
I am stirred like a bee, which sometimes defends honey with its sting.

463
00:47:12,719 --> 00:47:18,374
But consider the letters from both sides; you will soon see whether we are arming the page with barbs or flowers.

464
00:47:18,374 --> 00:47:21,626
The Apostle indeed speaks of similar people who must be silenced.

465
00:47:21,626 --> 00:47:22,177
Titus 1:11.

466
00:47:22,177 --> 00:47:23,078
But pay attention.

467
00:47:23,078 --> 00:47:26,631
We fight with you like doves, more with our mouths than with our teeth.

468
00:47:26,631 --> 00:47:29,033
If only it were true that you want to be taught!

469
00:47:29,033 --> 00:47:33,187
I would already be offering you the holy anointing of the Spirit with my own hands.

470
00:47:33,187 --> 00:47:33,937
Do you love me?

471
00:47:33,937 --> 00:47:35,438
I have not harmed you, I know.

472
00:47:35,438 --> 00:47:39,992
But you would truly love me if you did not think differently and approached my work kindly.

473
00:47:39,992 --> 00:47:42,395
Are you surprised that I like Cyprian's letters?

474
00:47:42,395 --> 00:47:46,098
Why wouldn’t I like the letters of a blessed martyr and a Catholic priest?

475
00:47:46,098 --> 00:47:47,449
You mention Novatian to me?

476
00:47:47,449 --> 00:47:53,004
I hear he was a philosopher of the world; nor am I surprised that he strayed from the Church of the living God.

477
00:47:53,004 --> 00:48:09,018
I know he abandoned the root of the ancient law, the source of the old people, envying Cornelius, accommodating Novatus’s madness, and became a bishop without legitimate consecration, and therefore was not made one through the letter of those who pretended to be Confessors, who would tear apart the limbs of one mother.

478
00:48:09,018 --> 00:48:13,822
These things, brother, I will prove to you with the confession of your own people, with letters.

479
00:48:13,822 --> 00:48:23,030
Thus, your philosopher, seeking to establish his own wisdom, as the Apostle says, is not subject to the wisdom of God; for in his wisdom, the world did not recognize the wisdom of God.

480
00:48:23,030 --> 00:48:23,630
Romans 10:3.

481
00:48:25,031 --> 00:49:36,741
Because you think Novatian suffered before Cyprian, and you add that Cyprian said, "My adversary preceded me," see how clearly I respond. Novatian never suffered martyrdom, nor was this ever heard or read from the words of the most blessed Cyprian.
You have his letters in which he speaks of Cornelius, the bishop of Rome, whom Novatian envied at the time. Cornelius resisted hostile leaders, often confessed, was often tormented; he led many Confessors and Martyrs, and was crowned most gloriously with many while Novatian was still alive and even unconcerned. Novatian had left the church of Christ to avoid the burden of confession. Initially provoked by envy, he could not endure the episcopate of Cornelius; then he committed himself to Novatus, mocked by the letters of a few. All these things about Novatian, Cyprian's letters will teach you thoroughly.
Furthermore, even if Novatian did suffer something, he was not killed; even if he was killed, he was not crowned. Why? Because he was outside the peace of the Church, outside harmony, outside the mother of whom a martyr should be a part. Listen to the Apostle: "And if I have all faith, so as to move mountains, but do not have love, I am nothing. And if I give away all my possessions to feed the poor, and if I hand over my body to be burned, but do not have love, I gain nothing" (First Corinthians 13:2-3).

482
00:49:36,741 --> 00:49:41,762
However, Cyprian suffered in the harmony of all, in common peace, among the group of Confessors.

483
00:49:41,762 --> 00:49:48,195
He often confessed under repeated persecutions, was tormented with much laceration, and finally was offered the saving cup.

484
00:49:48,195 --> 00:49:49,398
This was to be crowned.

485
00:49:49,398 --> 00:49:57,296
Therefore, let Novatian keep his letters; his arrogance and pride, which, while lifting him high, cast him down; while he spares no one, he is spilled.

486
00:49:57,296 --> 00:50:00,748
Behold, he who inexorably closes the way of salvation to brothers!

487
00:50:00,748 --> 00:50:05,822
Behold, he who confidently claims to carry himself openly and cleanse the Lord's threshing floor!

488
00:50:05,822 --> 00:50:16,073
Have mercy on yourself, brother Sympronian, and do not let Novatian deceive you under this facade; and let him not be considered more righteous because he despises others by comparison to himself.

489
00:50:16,439 --> 00:50:22,639
Often, boldness pretends to be confidence; and to those desperate sinners, a false image of a good conscience flatters them.

490
00:50:22,639 --> 00:50:29,989
On the other hand, all humility is innocence, even that which owes a debt, even that which sins, even that which flatters its soul with the sinner.

491
00:50:29,989 --> 00:50:35,888
Moses said, Erase me from the book you have written, so that sinners might not perish (Exodus thirty-two, thirty-two).

492
00:50:35,888 --> 00:50:43,438
The Apostle said, I wished that I myself were accursed in Christ for the sake of my brothers, my relatives according to the flesh (Romans nine, three).

493
00:50:43,438 --> 00:50:48,788
Certainly, both are praying on behalf of sinners; and because of this, neither Moses nor Paul offended God.

494
00:50:48,788 --> 00:50:50,238
Is Novatian better than them?

495
00:50:50,238 --> 00:50:51,588
A reformer of the Prophets?

496
00:50:51,588 --> 00:50:52,888
A teacher of the Apostles?

497
00:50:52,888 --> 00:50:55,187
Does he now seem to be with Christ like Moses?

498
00:50:55,187 --> 00:50:57,637
Does he now ascend to the third heaven like Paul?

499
00:50:57,637 --> 00:50:59,887
Is he now heard alone, neglecting all others?

500
00:50:59,887 --> 00:51:02,137
This should be enough to answer your letters.

501
00:51:02,137 --> 00:51:14,386
But because you argued more extensively about not doing penance, or doing it before baptism; and filled the page of the treatise with many chapters of examples, I will respond to each abundantly: I will not be silent about what true faith holds.

502
00:51:14,386 --> 00:51:18,486
You, as you generously commanded our hearing, offer a kind return to the treatise.

503
00:51:18,486 --> 00:51:24,936
Perhaps the Lord will provide that we who have patiently presented ourselves to you, may also reap some fruit from your patience.

504
00:51:24,936 --> 00:51:31,236
May the Lord deign to guard and protect you forever, and make you live as a Christian and Catholic, and be in harmony with us.

505
00:51:31,236 --> 00:51:31,486
Amen.

506
00:51:31,486 --> 00:51:41,335
Have mercy on yourself, brother Sympronian, and do not let Novatian deceive you under this pretense; and therefore be considered more righteous, because he despised others in comparison to himself.

507
00:51:41,335 --> 00:51:47,535
Often, boldness pretends to be confidence; and to those desperate sinners, a false image of a good conscience flatters them.

508
00:51:47,535 --> 00:51:54,884
On the other hand, all humility is innocence, even that which owes a debt, even that which sins, even that which flatters its soul with the sinner.

509
00:51:54,884 --> 00:52:00,784
Moses said, Erase me from the book you have written, so that sinners might not perish (Exodus thirty-two, thirty-two).

510
00:52:00,784 --> 00:52:08,334
The Apostle said, I wished that I myself were accursed in Christ for the sake of my brothers, my relatives according to the flesh (Romans nine, three).

511
00:52:09,383 --> 00:52:14,058
Of course, both pray for sinners; and because of this, neither Moses nor Paul offended God.

512
00:52:14,058 --> 00:52:17,038
Is Novatian better than them? A corrector of the Prophets?

513
00:52:17,038 --> 00:52:18,373
A teacher of the Apostles?

514
00:52:18,373 --> 00:52:20,839
Has he already been seen with Christ like Moses?

515
00:52:20,839 --> 00:52:23,870
Has he already been elevated to the third heaven like Paul?

516
00:52:23,870 --> 00:52:26,438
Has he been heard alone, neglecting everyone else?

517
00:52:26,438 --> 00:52:28,904
This should suffice in response to your letters.

518
00:52:28,904 --> 00:52:41,284
But because you broadly debated about not doing penance, or doing it before baptism, and you filled the page of the treatise with many chapters of examples, I will respond to each abundantly: I will not be silent about what true faith holds.

519
00:52:41,284 --> 00:52:46,369
You, as you graciously commanded our hearing, kindly offer your graciousness again to the treatise.

520
00:52:46,369 --> 00:52:52,534
Perhaps the Lord will grant that we, who have patiently submitted to you, may also gain some benefit from your patience.

521
00:52:52,534 --> 00:52:59,058
May the Lord deign to keep and protect you forever, and make you live as a Christian and Catholic, and be in agreement with us.

522
00:52:59,058 --> 00:52:59,314
Amen.

523
00:52:59,879 --> 00:53:04,031
Letter Three Against the Treatises of the Novatians.

524
00:53:04,031 --> 00:53:07,115
Pacianus, bishop, sends greetings to his brother Sympronian.

525
00:53:07,115 --> 00:53:21,403
The entire treatise of the Novatians, which you have sent to me from all sides with propositions, my brother Sympronian, contains this: that it is not permitted to repent after baptism; that the Church cannot forgive mortal sin, and indeed that it perishes by accepting sinners.

526
00:53:21,403 --> 00:53:29,575
A remarkable honor, unique authority, and great constancy; to reject the guilty, to avoid the touch of sinners, and to mistakenly trust in one's own innocence.

527
00:53:29,575 --> 00:53:31,014
Who advocates this, brother?

528
00:53:31,014 --> 00:53:32,196
Moses, Paul, or Christ?

529
00:53:32,196 --> 00:53:43,914
Moses wished to be erased from the book for the sake of blasphemers Exodus thirty-two verse thirty-two,
Paul desired to be cursed for his brothers Romans nine verse three,
and the Lord Himself preferred to suffer for the unjust.

530
00:53:43,914 --> 00:53:45,097
None of these, you say.

531
00:53:45,097 --> 00:53:45,559
Who then?

532
00:53:45,559 --> 00:53:46,998
Novatian has commanded this.

533
00:53:46,998 --> 00:53:57,894
Someone pure and spotless, who has never heard of Novatus, who has never deserted the Church, who became a bishop by bishops, who was consecrated by the usual order, who succeeded to a vacant chair in the Church?

534
00:53:57,894 --> 00:53:59,282
What does it matter to you?

535
00:53:59,282 --> 00:54:00,824
you say; Novatian taught this.

536
00:54:00,824 --> 00:54:02,725
But when, brother, and in what times?

537
00:54:02,725 --> 00:54:04,627
Immediately after the Lord's passion?

538
00:54:04,627 --> 00:54:09,150
After the reign of Decius, that is, nearly three hundred years after the Lord's passion.

539
00:54:09,150 --> 00:54:09,664
What then?

540
00:54:09,664 --> 00:54:15,728
Did he follow prophets like the Cataphrygians, or some Philomena like Apelles; or did he alone receive such authority?

541
00:54:15,728 --> 00:54:16,962
Did he speak in tongues?

542
00:54:16,962 --> 00:54:17,784
Did he prophesy?

543
00:54:17,784 --> 00:54:19,018
Could he raise the dead?

544
00:54:19,018 --> 00:54:23,181
For he should have had some of these things to introduce a new law of the gospel.

545
00:54:23,181 --> 00:54:49,752
And even if the Apostle cries out against this, "Even if we, or an angel from heaven, preach a gospel contrary to the one we preached to you, let him be accursed" Galatians one verse eight.
Novatian understood it this way, you say: but Christ taught this.
So from Christ to the reign of Decius, no one understood?
After Decius, finally, every bishop was impatient; all others were dissolute who preferred to mix with the lost, who preferred to perish with the wretched, who preferred to be wounded by another's wound?

546
00:54:50,831 --> 00:55:02,822
The entire treatise of the Novatians that you, my brother Sympronian, have sent to me contains this: that repentance is not allowed after baptism, that the Church cannot forgive mortal sin, and that it perishes by accepting sinners.

547
00:55:02,822 --> 00:55:11,504
What an extraordinary honor, unique authority, and great steadfastness—to reject the guilty, to avoid the touch of sinners, and to wrongly trust in one's own innocence.

548
00:55:11,504 --> 00:55:14,088
Who supports this, brother—Moses, Paul, or Christ?

549
00:55:14,088 --> 00:55:22,771
But Moses wishes to be erased from the book for the blasphemers; and Paul wishes to be anathema for his brothers; and the Lord Himself prefers to suffer for the unjust.

550
00:55:22,771 --> 00:55:23,959
None of these, you say.

551
00:55:23,959 --> 00:55:24,424
Who then?

552
00:55:24,424 --> 00:55:25,665
Novatian commanded this.

553
00:55:25,665 --> 00:55:36,208
Someone immaculate and pure, who has not heard of Novatus, who has never deserted the Church, who became a bishop by bishops, who was consecrated by regular law, who obtained a vacant chair in the Church?

554
00:55:36,208 --> 00:55:37,086
What's it to you?

555
00:55:37,086 --> 00:55:38,637
you ask; Novatian taught this.

556
00:55:38,637 --> 00:55:40,549
But when, brother, and in what times?

557
00:55:40,549 --> 00:55:42,151
Right after the Lord's passion?

558
00:55:42,151 --> 00:55:45,924
No, after the reign of Decius, almost 300 years after the Lord's passion.

559
00:55:45,924 --> 00:55:46,441
What then?

560
00:55:46,441 --> 00:55:52,798
Did he follow prophets like the Cataphrygians, or some Philomena like Apelles; or did he himself receive so much authority?

561
00:55:52,798 --> 00:55:54,038
Did he speak in tongues?

562
00:55:54,038 --> 00:55:54,865
Did he prophesy?

563
00:55:54,865 --> 00:55:56,105
Could he raise the dead?

564
00:55:56,105 --> 00:56:00,550
For he ought to have had some of these abilities to introduce the gospel of a new law.

565
00:56:00,550 --> 00:56:35,642
And if the Apostle cries out against it: "Even if we, or an angel from heaven, preach a gospel to you other than what we have preached to you, let him be accursed." Novatian understood this, you say; but Christ taught this. Therefore, from Christ until the reign of Decius, no one understood? After Decius, finally, every bishop was impatient; all others were dissolute who preferred to mix with the lost, who preferred to perish with the wretched, who preferred to be wounded by another's wound? Under Novatian's rule, justice is liberated; under his leadership, everything that has gone astray is corrected.
Come on, you say, let us compete with examples and fight with reason.

566
00:56:36,623 --> 00:56:42,712
But I have been at peace up to this point, content with the tranquility of the ancient congregation of the Church.

567
00:56:42,712 --> 00:56:46,930
I have not engaged in studies of discord nor sought out arguments for disputes.

568
00:56:46,930 --> 00:56:59,320
After you were separated from the rest of the body and divided from the mother, to justify your actions, you began to diligently search through every corner of books, probing into hidden things, and disturbing whatever was at peace.

569
00:56:59,320 --> 00:57:03,272
Our ancestors did not engage in disputes; our security lies in simplicity.

570
00:57:03,272 --> 00:57:06,316
What fortified arguments have you brought from your side?

571
00:57:06,316 --> 00:57:12,457
I do not know what Novatian did, what Novatus admitted, what Evaristus boasted about, or what Nicostratus declared.

572
00:57:12,457 --> 00:57:17,691
Since I ignore your weapons, I am not familiar with them; see if you can clash with unarmed truth.

573
00:57:17,691 --> 00:57:21,322
Nonetheless, let’s wait to hear what you object to and what you say.

574
00:57:21,322 --> 00:57:24,153
Could bare truth or innocent ignorance even stand up?

575
00:57:24,153 --> 00:57:34,460
You propose, and rightly so, that the Church is a people renewed by water and the Holy Spirit, without denying the name of Christ, a temple and house of God, the pillar and foundation of truth.

576
00:57:34,460 --> 00:57:36,275
First Timothy chapter 3, verse 15.

577
00:57:36,275 --> 00:57:40,815
A holy virgin with the purest thoughts, the bride of Christ from His bones and flesh.

578
00:57:40,815 --> 00:57:42,417
Ephesians chapter 5, verse 30.

579
00:57:42,417 --> 00:57:43,698
Without spot or wrinkle.

580
00:57:43,698 --> 00:57:45,301
Ephesians chapter 5, verse 27.

581
00:57:45,301 --> 00:57:47,597
Adhering to the full rights of the Gospels.

582
00:57:47,597 --> 00:57:48,932
Who among us denies this?

583
00:57:48,932 --> 00:57:52,777
Moreover, we add that the Church is a queen in golden and varied attire.

584
00:57:52,777 --> 00:57:53,792
Psalm 45, verse 10.

585
00:57:53,792 --> 00:57:56,408
A fruitful vine on the sides of the Lord's house.

586
00:57:56,408 --> 00:57:57,423
Psalm 128, verse 3.

587
00:57:57,423 --> 00:57:59,346
The Mother of countless young women.

588
00:57:59,346 --> 00:58:01,215
Song of Solomon chapter 6, verse 7.

589
00:58:01,215 --> 00:58:03,885
The one beautiful dove of her mother, and perfect.

590
00:58:03,885 --> 00:58:05,754
Song of Solomon chapter 6, verse 9.

591
00:58:05,754 --> 00:58:12,483
She is the mother of all, built on the foundations of the Prophets and Apostles, with Jesus Christ Himself as the cornerstone.

592
00:58:12,483 --> 00:58:14,085
Ephesians chapter 2, verse 20.

593
00:58:14,085 --> 00:58:16,702
A great house enriched with a variety of vessels.

594
00:58:16,702 --> 00:58:20,226
Come, you say, let us contend with examples and fight with reason.

595
00:58:20,226 --> 00:58:26,315
But I have been at peace up to this point: content with the tranquility of the ancient congregation of the Church.

596
00:58:26,315 --> 00:58:30,533
I have not engaged in studies of discord nor sought out arguments for disputes.

597
00:58:32,135 --> 00:58:40,736
After you were separated from the rest of the body and divided from the mother, you diligently search through all the recesses of books to explain your actions.

598
00:58:40,736 --> 00:58:44,392
You seek out hidden things and disturb whatever is otherwise secure.

599
00:58:44,392 --> 00:58:47,241
Our ancestors did not engage in unnecessary disputes.

600
00:58:47,241 --> 00:58:48,961
Our security is straightforward.

601
00:58:48,961 --> 00:58:51,219
What fortified arguments have you brought?

602
00:58:51,219 --> 00:58:57,186
I do not know what Novatian did, what Novatus committed, what Evaristus inflated, or what Nicostratus reported.

603
00:58:57,186 --> 00:58:59,766
While I disregard your arms, I do not know them.

604
00:58:59,766 --> 00:59:01,809
See if you contend with unarmed truth.

605
00:59:01,809 --> 00:59:04,980
Let us wait, however, for what you object to, what you say.

606
00:59:04,980 --> 00:59:08,044
Could naked truth or innocent ignorance stand on its own?

607
00:59:08,044 --> 00:59:19,226
You propose, and rightly so, that the Church is a people renewed by water and the Holy Spirit, without denying the name of Christ, a temple and house of God, the pillar and foundation of truth 1 Timothy 3:15.

608
00:59:19,226 --> 00:59:29,278
A holy virgin with the purest thoughts, the bride of Christ from His bones and flesh Ephesians 5:30, without spot or wrinkle Ephesians 5:27, faithfully preserving the laws of the Gospels.

609
00:59:29,278 --> 00:59:30,622
Who among us denies this?

610
00:59:30,622 --> 00:59:45,835
We even add that the Church is a queen in a golden and multicolored robe Psalm 45:10, a fruitful vine on the sides of the Lord's house Psalm 128:3, the mother of young maidens beyond number Song of Solomon 6:7, a unique, beautiful dove of her mother, and perfect Song of Solomon 6:8.

611
00:59:45,835 --> 00:59:53,307
The very mother of all, built on the foundations of the Prophets and Apostles, with Jesus Christ Himself as the cornerstone Ephesians 2:20.

612
00:59:53,307 --> 00:59:55,941
A great house enriched with all kinds of vessels.

613
00:59:55,941 --> 00:59:57,769
But these are our arguments later.

614
00:59:57,769 --> 00:59:59,166
For now, let us see yours.

615
00:59:59,166 --> 01:00:02,446
The Church is a people reborn from water and the Holy Spirit.

616
01:00:02,446 --> 01:00:02,714
Fine.

617
01:00:02,714 --> 01:00:04,112
Who closed God's fountain?

618
01:00:04,112 --> 01:00:05,456
Who took away the Spirit?

619
01:00:05,456 --> 01:00:09,488
Indeed, with us, there is living water, the very one springing from Christ.

620
01:00:09,488 --> 01:00:13,035
You, separated from the eternal fountain, from where are you born?

621
01:00:13,035 --> 01:00:15,723
The Holy Spirit has not left the principal mother.

622
01:00:15,723 --> 01:00:16,852
How did He reach you?

623
01:00:16,852 --> 01:00:25,722
Unless perhaps He followed you in discord, content with an unconsecrated seat, having abandoned so many priests, and loved a worn-out pond of a counterfeit fountain.

624
01:00:27,119 --> 01:00:31,241
Your people, where do they receive the Spirit that is not anointed by a priest?

625
01:00:31,241 --> 01:00:34,475
Where do they get the water that has departed from the source?

626
01:00:34,475 --> 01:00:38,023
Where is the renewal that has lost the cradle of the bride of peace?

627
01:00:38,023 --> 01:00:41,048
The Church is a people who do not deny the name of Christ.

628
01:00:41,048 --> 01:00:45,222
Do we not have among us confessors who were tested by chains, fires, and swords?

629
01:00:45,222 --> 01:00:48,665
You might say, they were, but by accepting deniers, they perished.

630
01:00:48,665 --> 01:00:57,794
I won't remain silent about the fact that even Novatian, when he was still in the Church, wrote, advised, and read the document about accepting back the deniers or the fallen.

631
01:00:57,794 --> 01:01:02,437
Meanwhile, whom can you convince that the whole Church collapsed by accepting the fallen?

632
01:01:02,437 --> 01:01:05,985
That by admitting penitents, those who admitted them became deniers?

633
01:01:05,985 --> 01:01:13,549
And if some people were more lenient, did the others who did not approve their actions but followed the custom and peace lose the Christian name?

634
01:01:13,549 --> 01:02:19,542
Hear the voice of Jeremiah: "In those days, they will not say, 'The fathers have eaten sour grapes, and the children's teeth are set on edge,' but everyone will die for their own sin."
Jeremiah 31:29-30.
Nor is the Lord silent in Ezekiel: "As the father’s soul, so also the son’s soul is mine. Everyone will die for their own sin."
Ezekiel 18:4.
And further down: "The son will not bear the iniquity of the father, nor will the father bear the iniquity of the son: the righteousness of the righteous will be upon them."
Ezekiel 18:20.
You yourself cite this example: "And if these three men were in its midst, Noah, Job, and Daniel, they would not save sons or daughters; they alone would be saved."
Ezekiel 14:16.
Behold, they are saved who are placed among sinners, who cannot save others. You bind the whole world with the chains of a few; you condemn the whole Church with the weakness of a small portion.
What of all the saints with you, whom Novatus trained, whom Evaristus chose, whom Nicostratus taught, whom Novatian instructed? You reject thorns and thistles. You do not have weeds in your crop. For you, the grains are already purified. The one who purifies will come to you without a winnowing fan.
Matthew 3:12.
Will you alone among all not have chaff?

635
01:02:20,063 --> 01:02:23,620
But let’s leave our things for later; for now, let’s focus on yours.

636
01:02:23,620 --> 01:02:27,072
The Church is the community reborn from water and the Holy Spirit.

637
01:02:27,072 --> 01:02:28,902
So, who has blocked God’s fountain?

638
01:02:28,902 --> 01:02:30,471
Who has taken the Spirit away?

639
01:02:30,471 --> 01:02:35,178
On the contrary, among us, there is living water, the very water that springs from Christ.

640
01:02:35,178 --> 01:02:38,891
You, separated from the eternal source, where are you regenerated from?

641
01:02:38,891 --> 01:02:42,657
The Holy Spirit has not left the original mother: how does He reach you?

642
01:02:42,657 --> 01:02:50,554
Unless perhaps He followed someone discordant, content with a seat not consecrated by so many priests, and loved the worn-out pool of a false fountain.

643
01:02:50,554 --> 01:02:55,627
Where does your community get the Spirit; the people whom an anointed priest does not consecrate?

644
01:02:55,627 --> 01:02:58,974
Where do they get the water, which has departed from the mother?

645
01:02:58,974 --> 01:03:02,897
Where do they get renewal, which has lost the cradle of the peaceful bride?

646
01:03:02,897 --> 01:03:09,852
The Church is a community without denying the name of Christ: are there not confessors among us, proven by chains, fires, and swords?

647
01:03:09,852 --> 01:03:13,879
You will say, they existed, but by accepting those who denied, they perished.

648
01:03:13,879 --> 01:03:23,503
I won’t even mention that, indeed, Novatianus of your group, when he was still in the Church, both wrote and advised and read a document about accepting those who had denied or lapsed.

649
01:03:23,503 --> 01:03:28,889
Meanwhile, how can you persuade anyone that the entire Church has fallen by accepting those who lapsed?

650
01:03:28,889 --> 01:03:32,707
That by admitting the penitent, the admitting people have become deniers?

651
01:03:32,707 --> 01:03:40,500
And if some people have been more lenient, have the rest who did not approve of their actions but followed custom and peace, lost the Christian name?

652
01:03:40,500 --> 01:03:50,855
Hear the voice of Jeremiah: "In those days, they will not say, 'The fathers have eaten sour grapes, and the children's teeth are set on edge,' but each will die for his own sin" (Jeremiah 31:29-30).

653
01:03:50,855 --> 01:03:59,014
Nor is the Lord silent through Ezekiel: "Just as the soul of the father, so also the soul of the son is mine. Each will die for his own sin" (Ezekiel 18:4).

654
01:03:59,014 --> 01:04:08,637
Further down: "The son will not bear the iniquity of the father, nor will the father bear the iniquity of the son: The righteousness of the righteous will be upon him" (Ezekiel 18:20).

655
01:04:08,637 --> 01:04:17,842
You even cite this example: "Even if these three men were in it, Noah, Job, and Daniel, they would not save their sons or daughters; they alone would be saved" (Ezekiel 14:16).

656
01:04:18,887 --> 01:04:23,394
Here are the ones who are saved, who are in the midst of sinners and cannot save others.

657
01:04:23,394 --> 01:04:29,385
You bind the whole world with the chains of a few; you condemn the whole Church with the weakness of a small portion.

658
01:04:29,385 --> 01:04:36,451
What about all the saints with you, those whom Novatus taught, whom Evaristus chose, whom Nicostratus instructed, whom Novatianus trained?

659
01:04:36,451 --> 01:04:42,442
You have avoided thorns and thistles; you don't have weeds among your crops; for you, the grains are already cleaned.

660
01:04:42,442 --> 01:04:47,256
The purifier will come to you without a winnowing fan; will you be the only one without chaff?

661
01:04:47,256 --> 01:04:50,123
Come on, say the rest: the Church is the body of Christ.

662
01:04:50,123 --> 01:04:57,497
Indeed, a body, not a part; a body gathered from many parts and members into one, as the Apostle says: For the body is not one member, but many.

663
01:04:57,497 --> 01:05:03,078
Therefore, the Church is a full body, both a body and a solid one, already spread throughout the whole world.

664
01:05:03,078 --> 01:05:10,759
Like a city, I say, whose parts are united; not like you Novatians, an insolent little part and lump gathered and separated from the rest of the body.

665
01:05:10,759 --> 01:05:23,151
The Church is the temple of God; certainly a spacious temple, a great house, having indeed vessels of gold and silver, but also wooden and earthenware ones, some for honor, but many magnificent ones destined for various uses of various works.

666
01:05:23,151 --> 01:05:27,248
The Church is a holy virgin, with the most chaste feelings, the bride of Christ.

667
01:05:27,248 --> 01:05:29,296
A virgin; it is true: but also a mother.

668
01:05:29,296 --> 01:05:35,748
A bride; it is clear: but also a wife and partner taken from her husband; therefore bone of his bones, and flesh of his flesh.

669
01:05:35,748 --> 01:05:43,019
For David said about her: Your wife will be like a fruitful vine within your house; your children will be like olive shoots around your table.

670
01:05:43,019 --> 01:05:50,188
Therefore, this virgin has many offspring and countless children, with which the whole world is filled, always buzzing with populous swarms.

671
01:05:50,188 --> 01:06:01,914
This mother has great care for her children and a tender affection; the good are honored, the proud are punished, the sick are cared for; no one is lost, no one is despised; children are safely kept under the mother's indulgence.

672
01:06:01,914 --> 01:06:03,860
The Church is without spot or wrinkle.

673
01:06:04,679 --> 01:06:09,656
This means avoiding heresies, such as the Valentinians, the Cataphrygians, and the Novatians.

674
01:06:09,656 --> 01:06:14,847
Among these are some blemished and wrinkled folds, envious of the ornaments of precious garments.

675
01:06:14,847 --> 01:06:22,767
However, the sinner and the penitent are not a stain on the Church; because as long as he sins and does not repent, he is placed outside the Church.

676
01:06:22,767 --> 01:06:25,122
When he stops sinning, he is already healed.

677
01:06:25,122 --> 01:06:30,580
But the heretic tears, disrupts, corrupts, and wrinkles the garment of the Lord, the Church of Christ.

678
01:06:30,580 --> 01:06:36,146
For when there are divisions and contentions among you, are you not carnal and walking according to man?

679
01:06:36,146 --> 01:06:37,323
First Corinthians 3:3.

680
01:06:37,323 --> 01:06:39,196
And their word spreads like cancer.

681
01:06:39,196 --> 01:06:40,267
Second Timothy 2:17.

682
01:06:40,267 --> 01:06:42,621
This is a stain on unity, this is a wrinkle.

683
01:06:42,621 --> 01:06:47,919
Finally, where the Apostle speaks about these things, he proposes the love of Christ and affection.

684
01:06:47,919 --> 01:06:51,665
Just as Christ, he says, loved the Church and gave himself up for her.

685
01:06:51,665 --> 01:06:52,468
Ephesians 5:25.

686
01:06:52,468 --> 01:06:55,786
To remove the heretics, because they did not know how to love.

687
01:06:55,786 --> 01:06:58,087
But why is this for the miserable penitent?

688
01:06:58,087 --> 01:07:00,388
Because he desires to love and to be loved.

689
01:07:00,388 --> 01:07:03,224
Come, say the rest:
The Church is the body of Christ.

690
01:07:03,224 --> 01:07:11,465
Certainly a body, not just a member: a body collected into one with many parts and members, as the Apostle says:
For the body is not one member, but many.

691
01:07:11,465 --> 01:07:12,750
First Corinthians 12:14.

692
01:07:12,750 --> 01:07:18,743
Therefore, the Church is a complete body, both unified and solid, and already spread throughout the whole world.

693
01:07:18,743 --> 01:07:26,610
Like a city, I say, whose parts are united; not like you Novatians, a certain insolent fragment and outgrowth, separated from the rest of the body.

694
01:07:26,610 --> 01:07:39,025
The Church is the temple of God: certainly a spacious temple, a great house, having indeed golden and silver vessels, but also wooden and earthen, some for honor, many indeed magnificent, destined for various uses in multiple works.

695
01:07:39,025 --> 01:07:40,095
Second Timothy 2:20.

696
01:07:40,095 --> 01:07:44,270
The Church is a holy virgin, with the most chaste senses, the bride of Christ.

697
01:07:44,270 --> 01:07:46,303
Virgin; it is true: but also a mother.

698
01:07:46,303 --> 01:07:52,992
Bride; it is evident: but also a wife and spouse taken from her husband: therefore bone of his bones, and flesh of his flesh.

699
01:07:52,992 --> 01:07:53,688
Genesis 2:23.

700
01:07:55,079 --> 01:08:03,986
For David spoke about this: "Your wife will be like a fruitful vine within your house; your children will be like young olive trees around your table." (Psalm 127:3).

701
01:08:03,986 --> 01:08:11,498
Thus, this virgin has many children and countless offspring, filling the whole world, always buzzing like a beehive with a large population.

702
01:08:11,498 --> 01:08:23,624
This mother has great care and tender affection for her children: the good are honored, the proud are punished, the sick are treated; no one is lost, no one is despised; secure offspring are kept under the mother’s indulgence.

703
01:08:23,624 --> 01:08:25,717
The Church is without stain or wrinkle.

704
01:08:25,717 --> 01:08:26,629
(Ephesians 5:27).

705
01:08:26,629 --> 01:08:30,761
That is, it has no heresies, no Valentinians, no Cataphrygians, no Novatians.

706
01:08:30,761 --> 01:08:36,019
For among them are certain stained and wrinkled parts, envying the ornaments of precious garments.

707
01:08:36,019 --> 01:08:43,370
However, a sinner and a penitent are not a stain on the Church; because as long as he sins and does not repent, he is outside the Church.

708
01:08:43,370 --> 01:08:45,731
When he stops sinning, he is already healed.

709
01:08:45,731 --> 01:08:51,204
But the heretic tears, intercepts, spoils, and wrinkles the garment of the Lord, the Church of Christ.

710
01:08:51,204 --> 01:08:56,730
For when there are divisions and disputes among you, are you not worldly and behaving like mere humans?

711
01:08:56,730 --> 01:08:58,018
(First Corinthians 3:3).

712
01:08:58,018 --> 01:09:00,003
And their talk spreads like gangrene.

713
01:09:00,003 --> 01:09:01,184
(Second Timothy 2:17).

714
01:09:01,184 --> 01:09:03,759
This is the stain of unity, this is the wrinkle.

715
01:09:03,759 --> 01:09:09,071
Finally, when the Apostle speaks about these things, he speaks of the love of Christ and affection.

716
01:09:09,071 --> 01:09:12,290
Just as Christ loved the Church and gave himself up for her.

717
01:09:12,290 --> 01:09:13,203
(Ephesians 5:25).

718
01:09:13,203 --> 01:09:16,529
To remove the heretics, because they did not know how to love.

719
01:09:16,529 --> 01:09:19,480
But why mention these things to the miserable penitent?

720
01:09:19,480 --> 01:09:21,841
Because he also wishes to love and be loved.

721
01:09:21,841 --> 01:09:24,739
The Church is whole, guarding the laws of the Gospels.

722
01:09:24,739 --> 01:09:27,851
Whole indeed because it is entire, because it is complete.

723
01:09:27,851 --> 01:09:43,518
Where rewards are given to the faithful, where tears are not denied to the miserable, where the sick are treated, where insolent health and proud justice claim nothing for themselves, where caring charity perseveres in all things, believing everything, hoping everything, enduring everything.

724
01:09:43,518 --> 01:09:44,860
(First Corinthians 13:7).

725
01:09:44,860 --> 01:09:52,586
Hence that saying of the Apostle: "Who is weak, and I am not weak? Who is led into sin, and I do not inwardly burn?" (Second Corinthians 11:29).

726
01:09:53,927 --> 01:09:59,176
Where the entire brotherhood bears its burdens together, grieving together, secure in mutual devotion.

727
01:09:59,176 --> 01:10:05,248
All supporting one another in love, making every effort to maintain the unity of the Spirit through the bond of peace.

728
01:10:05,248 --> 01:10:12,400
(Ephesians 4:3)
This will be the Church, my brother Sympronian; this will be the people reborn in Christ through water and the Holy Spirit.

729
01:10:12,400 --> 01:10:31,181
You say, "I do not know if a sin can be forgiven by bishops," since the Lord said, "Whoever denies me before men, I also will deny before my Father who is in heaven." (Matthew 10:33)
Why then did your Novatian, not even a legitimate bishop at that time, long before Cornelius became bishop of Rome, long before he envied Cornelius' priesthood, propose these things?

730
01:10:31,181 --> 01:10:34,834
You have the testimony of Cyprian; Cyprian whom you could never defame.

731
01:10:34,834 --> 01:11:48,414
For in one place, he wrote to Antonianus in this manner:
"It was also added while Novatian was writing then; and what he wrote, he read aloud with his own voice; and Moses, who was then a confessor and now already a martyr, signed it; that peace should be given to those who had lapsed, who were weak and at the point of death: these letters were sent throughout the whole world and brought to the attention of all churches."
What do you say, my brother Sympronian? Novatian wrote these things, and to add the service of pure will, he also read them aloud. His right hand is a witness, the hand that wrote, is a witness: the tongue that read is a witness. Cornelius, for whom all this envy of yours erupted, was not yet a bishop. Much later, with many fellow bishops, with many confessors, and immediately with martyrs, as the same Cyprian writes, he agreed with the advice of the elders that it was permissible to grant peace.
If the door to repentance is to be closed, Novatian is guilty, who wrote, proposed, and read these things. Where then was the impatient rigor? Where was that fierce judgment? If no one had preferred Cornelius to you, the authority of the writer would remain. Now the whole opinion is displeasing, now weapons are thrown at us, supplied by the very authority by which the cause of the weapons prevailed.
The Church is, keeping the full rights of the Gospels. Whole indeed because complete, because full.

732
01:11:48,671 --> 01:12:04,031
Where the reward is given to the faithful, where tears are not denied to the miserable, where the sick are healed, where insolent health and proud justice claim nothing for themselves, where caring love perseveres in all things, believing all things, hoping all things, enduring all things.

733
01:12:04,031 --> 01:12:05,249
First Corinthians 13:7.

734
01:12:05,249 --> 01:12:08,532
Hence the Apostle's statement: Who is weak, and I am not weak?

735
01:12:08,532 --> 01:12:10,386
Who is offended, and I do not burn?

736
01:12:10,386 --> 01:12:11,710
Second Corinthians 11:29.

737
01:12:11,710 --> 01:12:15,894
Where the whole brotherhood bears its burdens together, sharing in mutual care.

738
01:12:15,894 --> 01:12:21,243
All supporting each other in love, striving to maintain the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace.

739
01:12:21,243 --> 01:12:21,985
Ephesians 4:3.

740
01:12:21,985 --> 01:12:28,340
This will be the Church, brother Sympronian; this will be the people reborn in Christ through water and the Holy Spirit.

741
