742
01:13:44,447 --> 01:13:47,844
Where then is the impatient severity? Where is that fierce judgment?

743
01:13:47,844 --> 01:13:52,339
If no one had preferred Cornelius to you, the authority of the writer would have remained.

744
01:13:52,339 --> 01:13:59,181
Now the entire opinion is displeasing, and weapons are being hurled at us by the very people whose authority once strengthened our cause.

745
01:13:59,181 --> 01:14:01,129
But when did the Novatian heresy begin?

746
01:14:01,129 --> 01:14:04,376
Listen, please, and understand the entire sequence of your error.

747
01:14:04,376 --> 01:14:09,320
Cornelius, already made bishop of Rome by sixteen bishops, had taken the place of the vacant chair.

748
01:14:09,320 --> 01:14:14,864
In that same virginal purity with which he was endowed, he endured frequent persecutions from an angry emperor.

749
01:14:14,864 --> 01:14:30,897
Then, by chance, a certain priest named Novatus from Africa, who had defrauded widows in the Carthaginian church, robbed orphans, withheld church money, thrown his father out of the house, causing him to die of hunger without burial, and struck his pregnant wife's womb with a kick, causing her to miscarry, came to Rome.

750
01:14:30,897 --> 01:14:34,942
While in Carthage, as the day of his trial in the church was approaching, he hid.

751
01:14:34,942 --> 01:14:49,027
Not long after, he influenced this Novatian, who was anxious about Cornelius's bishopric (for he had hoped for it himself), and with some supporters on his side, as usually happens in such matters, he encouraged him, fueled his hesitation, and urged him to hope for something great.

752
01:14:49,027 --> 01:14:57,018
He found some of those who had escaped the storm of that persecution, among whom he could stir up jealousy against Cornelius for accepting those who had lapsed.

753
01:14:57,018 --> 01:14:58,716
He sent their letters to Novatian.

754
01:14:58,716 --> 01:15:12,052
Based on the authority of these letters, even though there was already a bishop in Rome, he assumed the title of another bishop for himself, against the singular priesthood’s rules: he accused Cornelius of communing with the lapsed and claimed himself to be innocent.

755
01:15:12,052 --> 01:15:15,748
Against him, I must give an account, defend my modesty, and clear my life.

756
01:15:15,748 --> 01:15:17,695
But when did the Novatian heresy begin?

757
01:15:17,695 --> 01:15:20,942
Listen, please, and understand the entire sequence of your error.

758
01:15:20,942 --> 01:15:25,886
Cornelius, already made bishop of Rome by sixteen bishops, had taken the place of the vacant chair.

759
01:15:25,886 --> 01:15:31,430
In that same virginal purity with which he was endowed, he endured frequent persecutions from an angry emperor.

760
01:15:32,279 --> 01:15:49,090
Then, by chance, a certain priest named Novatus from Africa, who had defrauded widows in the church of Carthage, robbed orphans, denied the church's money, thrown his father out of the house, and caused his father to die of hunger without burial, and who had kicked his pregnant wife in the womb causing a miscarriage, came to Rome.

761
01:15:49,090 --> 01:15:54,760
And when in Carthage, as the brothers in the church pressed on him, the day of his trial approached, and he hid.

762
01:15:54,760 --> 01:16:08,786
Not long after, he incited Novatian, who was anxious about the bishopric of Cornelius (for he hoped for it himself) and, as often happens in such matters, he swayed some followers to his side, encouraging and supporting the doubtful one; urging him to hope for something great.

763
01:16:08,786 --> 01:16:17,140
He found some among those who had escaped the storm of that persecution; through whom he could stir up envy against Cornelius regarding the acceptance of the lapsed.

764
01:16:17,140 --> 01:16:18,862
He sent their letters to Novatian.

765
01:16:18,862 --> 01:16:31,823
Using the authority of these letters, while the bishop was already sitting in Rome, Novatian assumed the title of another bishop, which was contrary to the singular priesthood, accusing Cornelius of communing with the lapsed and claiming his own innocence.

766
01:16:31,823 --> 01:16:38,051
Against this man, I must give an account, against this man, I must assert my honor, against this man, I must clear my life.

767
01:16:38,051 --> 01:17:31,013
But you may say, "You bishops, why do you approve such things?" Let someone else say this: you defend Novatian. This cause may seem inexcusable to others, though it may be pleasing to you. Anyone who is innocent for you is guilty for another. Do not accuse someone else of a crime from which you cannot be freed. Come on, as bishops, we must owe all modesty, for we have received the name of the apostles, for we are marked by the title of Christ.
The Lord denies the denier, you say; you should not acknowledge the denier. Who acknowledges the denier? The one who drives him to repentance, rebukes, shows the crime, opens the wounds, reminds him of eternal punishments, corrects him by the destruction of the flesh? This is chastising, not acknowledging.
The Lord says to us, "You are the salt of the earth" Therefore, by rightly speaking these things, we do not become worthless, and anyone who hears will not be worthless. You see, we do not trample on the Lord's judgment, but we approve it; we do not reject severity, but we reveal His will.

768
01:17:31,367 --> 01:17:37,704
But to the penitent,
you will say, you forgive sins; when it is only in baptism that you are allowed to forgive sin.

769
01:17:37,704 --> 01:17:44,149
Not by me, clearly, but by God alone, who both grants pardon in baptism and does not reject the tears of the penitent.

770
01:17:44,149 --> 01:17:51,086
Moreover, what I do, I do not by my own authority, but by the Lord's:
We are God’s co-workers, He says, you are God’s building.

771
01:17:51,086 --> 01:18:01,246
First Corinthians 3:9
And again: I planted, Apollos watered, but God gave the growth:
So neither the one who plants nor the one who waters is anything, but only God who gives the growth.

772
01:18:01,246 --> 01:18:08,346
First Corinthians 3:6-7
So whether we baptize, urge repentance, or grant pardon to the penitent;
we do this by Christ's authority.

773
01:18:08,346 --> 01:18:12,443
You must consider whether Christ can do this, whether Christ has done this.

774
01:18:12,443 --> 01:18:15,666
But you will say, bishops, why do you approve such actions?

775
01:18:15,666 --> 01:18:18,233
Let someone else say this: you defend Novatian.

776
01:18:18,233 --> 01:18:22,384
This cause may seem inexcusable to others, though it may be pleasing to you.

777
01:18:22,384 --> 01:18:25,935
Let anyone be innocent for you, whoever is guilty on your behalf.

778
01:18:25,935 --> 01:18:29,431
Do not accuse another of a crime from which you cannot be freed.

779
01:18:29,431 --> 01:18:36,804
Come, let us bishops show all our modesty, because we have received the title of apostles, because we are marked by the name of Christ.

780
01:18:36,804 --> 01:18:40,901
You say the Lord denies the denier: you, I do not want to admit the denier.

781
01:18:40,901 --> 01:18:42,267
Who confesses the denier?

782
01:18:42,267 --> 01:18:50,842
The one who urges repentance, reproaches, shows the crime, reveals the wounds, reminds of eternal punishments, corrects through the destruction of the flesh?

783
01:18:50,842 --> 01:18:52,699
This is to chastise, not to admit.

784
01:18:52,699 --> 01:18:55,485
The Lord says to us: You are the salt of the earth.

785
